{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d9cce23d-4f66-4d44-a12e-b3c86808f8ce","content":"Here's a concise approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Get a shell into the container\n```powershell\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` in the container\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process ID\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### 5. Copy the trace file out\n```powershell\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Tips\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't on PATH, use the full path: `$env:USERPROFILE\\.dotnet\\tools\\dotnet-trace`.\n- For **event-based** profiling (GC, exceptions, contention), use `--profile gc-verbose` or a custom `--providers` list.\n- If you can't install tools in the container, enable **EventPipe** via environment variables before the app starts:\n  ```\n  DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1\n  DOTNET_EventPipeOutputPath=C:\\trace.nettrace\n  ```\n- **PerfView** (`PerfView.exe collect`) is another option if you can copy it into the container — it gives richer ETW data on Windows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6bb6510f-9c07-4b7f-8ef2-f51f54abb92a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":471,"requestId":"6091:3AB79D:22FCC7:2D8823:69FFDE45"},"id":"4a28a72e-3492-46e9-a078-0807d3f85f37","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:24:32.373Z","parentId":"4be4048c-21f8-4266-8ce0-8d27ad37b617"}
